<file path=".ai/SRS-ADDENDUM-2.md">
# SRS Addendum 2 — TV-First Design, Unified Libraries & Input Systems

## CrispyTivi — Technology-Agnostic Requirements

**Supplements**: `.ai/SRS.md` + `.ai/SRS-ADDENDUM.md`
**Date**: 2026-03-14

---

## Table of Contents

1. [TV-First Design Philosophy](#1-tv-first-design-philosophy)
2. [Spatial Navigation System](#2-spatial-navigation-system)
3. [Input Device Abstraction](#3-input-device-abstraction)
4. [Unified Movie Library](#4-unified-movie-library)
5. [Unified Series Library](#5-unified-series-library)
6. [Multi-Source Live TV Experience](#6-multi-source-live-tv-experience)
7. [Source-Aware Filtering & Search](#7-source-aware-filtering--search)
8. [Metadata Enrichment](#8-metadata-enrichment)
9. [Standards & Compliance Reference](#9-standards--compliance-reference)

---

## 1. TV-First Design Philosophy

### 1.1 Core Principle

CrispyTivi is a **TV-first application**. Every screen, interaction, and component is designed for a 10-foot lean-back experience with a D-pad remote. Touch, mouse, and keyboard are supported but are secondary adaptations of the primary TV interface — never the other way around.

**Design hierarchy:**
1. TV with remote control (D-pad, OK, Back, color buttons, number keys) — PRIMARY
2. Console with gamepad (Xbox, PlayStation, Switch controllers) — SECONDARY
3. PC with keyboard, gamepad, remote, or pointing device — TERTIARY
4. Tablet/phone with touch — QUATERNARY (adapted from TV layout, not mobile-first)

### 1.2 Foundational Constraints

| Factor | Implication |
|---|---|
| Viewing distance: 2.5-3.5 meters | Text and interactive elements must be legible and operable from across the room — see Section 9 for platform minimums |
| D-pad input (4 directions + OK + Back) | No hover states; all features reachable via directional navigation |
| Shared screen (household) | No personal notifications visible during group viewing |
| No fine pointer | Every interactive element must be focusable and selectable via directional navigation |
| Cinematic context | Minimize UI chrome; maximize content surface area |
| Safe area / overscan | Content must respect platform-defined safe area margins — see Section 9 for platform values |

### 1.3 Design Rules

- REQ-TV-01: Every feature MUST be fully operable using only a 5-button remote (Up, Down, Left, Right, OK/Select) plus Back
- REQ-TV-02: No feature may require touch, mouse hover, or gestures as the only activation method
- REQ-TV-03: Maximum navigation depth MUST be 3 levels: Home → Category/List → Detail → Playback
- REQ-TV-04: Back button MUST always exit the current overlay/dialog before navigating backward through screen history
- REQ-TV-05: Back button from the root/home screen MUST show an "Exit app?" confirmation, never silently exit
- REQ-TV-06: The app MUST adapt gracefully when additional input methods are available (gamepad, keyboard, mouse, touch) without requiring them

---

## 2. Spatial Navigation System

### 2.1 Focus Model

The application MUST implement a spatial focus system where exactly one interactive element is "focused" at any time. Focus is the primary mechanism for user interaction on TV.

**Requirements:**

- REQ-NAV-01: Exactly one element MUST hold focus at all times when the app is in the foreground
- REQ-NAV-02: Focus MUST move in the direction of the pressed D-pad key to the nearest focusable element in that direction
- REQ-NAV-03: The focus computation algorithm MUST use weighted directional distance scoring: primary axis distance (direction of press) weighted ~3:1 over secondary axis (perpendicular offset)
- REQ-NAV-04: Focus MUST NOT move to elements that are outside the visible viewport without first scrolling them into view

### 2.2 Focus Zones

The screen MUST be organized into focus zones (traversal groups) that isolate navigation behavior.

- REQ-NAV-05: Each horizontal content row MUST be an isolated focus zone that remembers its last focused child
- REQ-NAV-06: When focus leaves a zone (via Up/Down between rows) and later returns, focus MUST restore to the last focused element within that zone
- REQ-NAV-07: The side navigation rail and content area MUST be separate focus zones
- REQ-NAV-08: Modal dialogs MUST trap focus — background elements become non-focusable while the modal is open
- REQ-NAV-09: When a modal closes, focus MUST restore to the element that had focus before the modal opened

### 2.3 Focus Visualization

- REQ-NAV-10: The focused element MUST be visually distinct from 3 meters viewing distance
- REQ-NAV-11: Focus indicator MUST use a combination of scale, colored border, and glow/shadow to be clearly identifiable from typical TV viewing distance
- REQ-NAV-12: Focus indicator contrast and minimum sizes — see Section "Standards & Compliance" at end of document
- REQ-NAV-13: Focus transition animation MUST be smooth and responsive — never laggy when navigating quickly, never jarring on single presses
- REQ-NAV-14: When D-pad is held and focus moves rapidly, animations MUST interrupt cleanly — never queue frames
- REQ-NAV-15: Focus indicator MUST NOT rely solely on color change — always combine with a geometric indicator (border, scale, or shadow)
- REQ-NAV-16: "Focused" state (currently highlighted) MUST be visually distinct from "Selected" state (previously chosen/active)
- REQ-NAV-17: Only `transform` (translate, scale, rotate) and `opacity` properties may be animated during focus transitions — never layout properties (width, height, padding, margin) that trigger reflow

### 2.4 Scroll Behavior

- REQ-NAV-18: Lists MUST scroll item-by-item when focus moves (not page-by-page by default)
- REQ-NAV-19: Page-by-page scroll (via bumper/trigger/PageUp/PageDown) MUST supplement item-by-item navigation, never replace it
- REQ-NAV-20: The focused item MUST always be fully visible — never partially clipped by the viewport edge
- REQ-NAV-21: Rows MUST show a partial peek of the next item to signal scrollability
- REQ-NAV-22: Scroll position MUST be remembered when navigating away from a screen and restored on return
- REQ-NAV-23: For lists with 1000+ items, only items within the viewport + 2 screens of buffer may be rendered (virtual/windowed rendering)
- REQ-NAV-24: Focus computation MUST remain imperceptibly fast with 1000+ focusable items — zone-scoped traversal or explicit index routing recommended for uniform grids

### 2.5 Row-Based Layout Navigation (Netflix Model)

- REQ-NAV-25: Left/Right MUST navigate within the current row, scrolling the row as needed
- REQ-NAV-26: Up/Down MUST move to the geometrically nearest item in the adjacent row (not necessarily the same column index)
- REQ-NAV-27: The first time a row receives focus, the default focused element MUST be the first (leftmost) item
- REQ-NAV-28: Each row MUST be an isolated focus zone — never place the entire screen in one flat traversal group

### 2.6 Grid Layout Navigation

- REQ-NAV-29: Focus traversal in uniform grids MUST follow natural reading order (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)
- REQ-NAV-30: Focus MUST NOT wrap at grid edges (leftmost to rightmost or vice versa) — wrapping causes disorientation
- REQ-NAV-31: When navigating between grid rows of different lengths, focus MUST clamp to the last item if the remembered column exceeds the row length

### 2.7 Side Navigation Rail

- REQ-NAV-32: The side rail MUST have a collapsed state (icon-only) always visible and an expanded state (icon + label)
- REQ-NAV-33: Left from the content's leftmost item MUST transfer focus to the rail's last focused item
- REQ-NAV-34: Right from the rail MUST return focus to the content's last focused item
- REQ-NAV-35: Selecting a rail item MUST navigate to that section, collapse the rail, and move focus to the content's default starting point

### 2.8 Tab Navigation

- REQ-NAV-36: Tabs MUST be navigable with Left/Right when the tab bar has focus
- REQ-NAV-37: Down from the tab bar MUST enter the tab's content; Up from the content's top element MUST return to the tab bar

### 2.9 Modal Dialogs

- REQ-NAV-38: Opening a modal MUST trap all focus inside it — background content becomes non-focusable
- REQ-NAV-39: Back/Escape MUST dismiss the modal and restore prior focus
- REQ-NAV-40: Initial focus in a dialog MUST land on the primary action button (e.g., "Confirm"), never a destructive action
- REQ-NAV-41: Directional keys MUST NOT dismiss a modal — only Back/Escape does

### 2.10 Seek Bar Interaction

- REQ-NAV-42: The seek bar MUST NOT receive focus accidentally — user must explicitly navigate Down to it from the OSD controls
- REQ-NAV-43: Left/Right on the focused seek bar MUST change position (10s per press; accelerating to 30s → 60s → 120s on held press)
- REQ-NAV-44: OK/Select on the seek bar MUST confirm the seek position and exit seek mode
- REQ-NAV-45: Back/Up from the seek bar MUST cancel seek (restore original position) and return focus to the control bar

### 2.11 Text Input on TV

- REQ-NAV-46: Text entry MUST use a full-screen overlay keyboard navigated with D-pad, not an inline text field
- REQ-NAV-47: Voice input MUST be the primary search method on platforms with microphone support
- REQ-NAV-48: Recent searches and suggestions MUST be offered to minimize keyboard use
- REQ-NAV-49: PIN entry MUST use a segmented digit display accepting direct number key presses (0-9)

### 2.12 Nested Scrollable Lists

- REQ-NAV-50: A horizontal row inside a vertical scroll MUST isolate its focus zone — Left/Right scrolls the row, Up/Down moves between rows
- REQ-NAV-51: The vertical scroll MUST only trigger when focus changes between row zones, not during intra-row navigation

