## 4. Unified Movie Library

### 4.1 Problem Statement

The same movie may exist across multiple sources (IPTV Provider A, IPTV Provider B, Plex server, Jellyfin server) at different quality levels and with different metadata. The movie library MUST present a single unified collection, not separate silos per source.

### 4.2 Canonical Entity Model

- REQ-LIB-01: Every movie MUST be represented as a single canonical entity regardless of how many sources provide it
- REQ-LIB-02: The canonical entity MUST use a stable external identifier as its deduplication key (TMDB ID as primary, IMDb ID as secondary)
- REQ-LIB-03: Each canonical entity MUST maintain an array of source records, each containing: source ID, source name, stream URL, quality tier, and codec info
- REQ-LIB-04: Canonical metadata (title, year, poster, backdrop, synopsis, genres, cast, director, rating) MUST come from the metadata enrichment service (TMDB), overriding provider-specific metadata

### 4.3 Deduplication Algorithm

Three-tier matching cascade, from most reliable to least:

| Tier | Method | Confidence | Auto-merge? |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | External ID match (TMDB ID or IMDb ID in provider metadata) | 0.99+ | Yes |
| 2 | Title exact match + Year match (after normalization) | 0.90-0.95 | Yes |
| 3 | Title fuzzy match (Levenshtein/Jaro-Winkler > 0.92) + Year | 0.70-0.85 | Flag for review |

**Title normalization rules:**
1. Strip HTML entities
2. Unicode NFC normalization
3. Lowercase
4. Remove punctuation: `. , : ; ! ? ' " ( ) [ ] { }`
5. Collapse multiple spaces to single space
6. Move leading articles to end: "The Matrix" → "matrix, the"
7. For matching: split tokens and sort alphabetically (enables word-order-independent comparison)

- REQ-LIB-05: Deduplication MUST occur at ingest time (during source sync), not at browse time
- REQ-LIB-06: Matches below 0.85 confidence MUST be queued for user review, never auto-merged
- REQ-LIB-07: Users MUST be able to manually merge two items (mark as same movie) or split auto-merged items (mark as different)
- REQ-LIB-08: Manual merge/split decisions MUST persist across re-syncs (stored as override flags)

### 4.4 Movie Detail Page (Universal Detail Page)

- REQ-LIB-09: Every movie MUST route to one canonical detail page with unified metadata from the enrichment service
- REQ-LIB-10: The detail page MUST show a "Watch on" section listing all available sources with quality badges (4K, FHD, HD, SD) and source names
- REQ-LIB-11: The best source MUST be auto-highlighted at the top of the list based on quality ranking
- REQ-LIB-12: Users MUST be able to override source selection per title ("Always play from [Source] for this movie")
- REQ-LIB-13: The Play button MUST resume from last position if watch history exists, regardless of which source was previously used

**Quality ranking for auto-selection (descending):**
1. 4K + Dolby Vision + Dolby Atmos
2. 4K + HDR10/HDR10+
3. 4K SDR
4. 1080p + HDR
5. 1080p SDR (high bitrate > 8 Mbps)
6. 1080p SDR (standard)
7. 720p
8. SD (480p or below)

Tie-break: user's source priority order (drag-to-reorder in Settings → Sources)

### 4.5 Browse Experience

- REQ-LIB-14: The movie grid MUST show unified content from all sources by default
- REQ-LIB-15: Movie cards MUST show the best available quality badge (4K/FHD/HD) in a corner
- REQ-LIB-16: When a movie exists on multiple sources, a small multi-source indicator (e.g., "3 sources" badge or stacked layers icon) MUST appear on the card
- REQ-LIB-17: Source-exclusive content (only on one source) SHOULD show "Only on [Source Name]" label
- REQ-LIB-18: Source health indicators MUST NOT appear on movie cards — only in Settings and as transient failover toasts

