## 1. Security & Privacy

### 1.1 Credential Storage

- REQ-SEC-01: All sensitive data (passwords, API tokens, PINs, MAC addresses, encryption keys) MUST be stored exclusively in the platform's hardware-backed secure storage (OS keychain/keystore equivalent) — never in plaintext files, preferences, or unencrypted databases
- REQ-SEC-02: Credentials MUST be erased from memory immediately after use — long-lived in-memory copies of secrets are prohibited
- REQ-SEC-03: No sensitive data may appear in application logs, crash reports, or debug output
- REQ-SEC-04: Biometric authentication (fingerprint, face recognition) SHOULD be available as an alternative to PIN for profile unlock on platforms with biometric hardware

### 1.2 Encryption

- REQ-SEC-05: The local database MUST be encrypted at rest using authenticated encryption (AES-256-GCM or equivalent)
- REQ-SEC-06: The database encryption key MUST itself be stored in the platform's secure storage
- REQ-SEC-07: All network communication MUST use TLS 1.2 minimum, TLS 1.3 preferred — TLS 1.0 and 1.1 MUST be rejected unconditionally
- REQ-SEC-08: Cloud sync payloads MUST be encrypted client-side before upload using authenticated encryption with a per-user key that never leaves the device
- REQ-SEC-09: For user-configured servers using self-signed certificates, the app MUST warn the user and support Trust-on-First-Use (store the accepted fingerprint securely; alert on mismatch)

### 1.3 PIN Security

- REQ-SEC-10: Profile PINs MUST be stored as salted hashes using a memory-hard key derivation function (Argon2id or bcrypt) — non-cryptographic hashes (FNV, CRC, MurmurHash) are prohibited for PIN storage
- REQ-SEC-11: Salt MUST be at least 16 bytes of cryptographically random data, stored alongside the hash
- REQ-SEC-12: PIN verification MUST use constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
- REQ-SEC-13: Progressive lockout MUST apply after consecutive failed PIN attempts (escalating cooldown periods; eventual lockout requiring account-level re-authentication)

### 1.4 Network Security

- REQ-SEC-14: Certificate pinning is NOT recommended for IPTV/media server endpoints (user-owned infrastructure with changing certificates). Instead, enforce Certificate Transparency, HSTS, and platform-level cleartext traffic blocking
- REQ-SEC-15: API authentication (for any app-owned backend) MUST use short-lived access tokens with refresh token rotation — refresh token reuse MUST invalidate the entire session family
- REQ-SEC-16: All user-provided URLs MUST be validated: accept only safe schemes (http, https, rtmp, rtmps); reject file://, javascript://, data:// and other dangerous schemes; sanitize path components against traversal attacks

### 1.5 App Security

- REQ-SEC-17: Release builds MUST use code obfuscation and symbol stripping
- REQ-SEC-18: Deep links MUST be validated as untrusted external input — parse, sanitize, and schema-validate all parameters before navigation or action
- REQ-SEC-19: If WebViews are used (e.g., OAuth login flows), file access, JavaScript interfaces, and navigation MUST be restricted to known safe domains
- REQ-SEC-20: Automated dependency vulnerability scanning MUST be part of the build pipeline; builds MUST fail on high-severity CVEs

### 1.6 Privacy Compliance

- REQ-SEC-21: The app MUST implement data minimization — collect only what is functionally necessary; map every stored field to a declared purpose
- REQ-SEC-22: Users MUST be able to export all their personal data in a structured, machine-readable format (JSON/CSV) via an in-app "Export my data" function
- REQ-SEC-23: Users MUST be able to delete all their data via an in-app "Delete all my data" function — deletion MUST cascade to cloud sync storage and be irreversible
- REQ-SEC-24: Data retention policies MUST be automated: watch history configurable (default 12 months), EPG cache pruned beyond 14 days, crash reports anonymized within 90 days
- REQ-SEC-25: Analytics/telemetry consent MUST be granular (separate toggles for crash reports, playback quality telemetry, engagement analytics) with no pre-ticked boxes
- REQ-SEC-26: The app MUST function fully regardless of analytics consent — no features gated behind consent
- REQ-SEC-27: Children's profiles MUST comply with COPPA: no behavioral tracking server-side, no persistent identifiers for profiling, no targeted advertising, parental consent required for data collection

### 1.7 Session Management

- REQ-SEC-28: A device management screen MUST show all devices that have accessed the account (name, type, last active, approximate location) with individual and bulk sign-out actions
- REQ-SEC-29: On credential change (password, PIN, server credentials), users MUST be notified on all active devices

---

## 2. Localization & Internationalization

### 2.1 Layout Direction

- REQ-I18N-01: The app MUST support full RTL (Right-to-Left) layout mirroring for Arabic, Hebrew, Persian, and Urdu
- REQ-I18N-02: All layout positioning MUST use directional abstractions (start/end, not left/right) so the entire UI mirrors automatically in RTL locales
- REQ-I18N-03: Icons with intrinsic directionality (play, skip, seek arrows, back/forward chevrons) MUST mirror in RTL; symmetric icons (pause, volume, settings) MUST NOT mirror
- REQ-I18N-04: The EPG timeline grid MUST reverse its time axis in RTL locales (earliest time on the right)
- REQ-I18N-05: Animations and transitions MUST respect layout direction (slide-in direction reverses in RTL)

### 2.2 Bidirectional Text

- REQ-I18N-06: Mixed-direction strings (e.g., Arabic text with English brand names like "قناة BBC عربي") MUST render correctly using Unicode bidirectional isolation
- REQ-I18N-07: Text input fields MUST auto-detect direction from the first strong character typed and align accordingly
- REQ-I18N-08: Numbers MUST remain LTR even in RTL context; Eastern Arabic numerals (٠١٢٣٤٥٦٧٨٩) MUST be used where the locale requires them

### 2.3 Script & Font Support

- REQ-I18N-09: The app MUST support rendering of Latin, Arabic (with full contextual shaping and ligatures), Hebrew, Devanagari, Thai, CJK (Chinese, Japanese, Korean), and Cyrillic scripts
- REQ-I18N-10: CJK text MUST carry locale tags to ensure correct regional glyph variants (same Unicode codepoint renders differently in Simplified Chinese vs Japanese)
- REQ-I18N-11: A font fallback chain MUST cover all supported scripts — prefer system fonts with bundled fallbacks for scripts not available on the platform

### 2.4 Date, Time & Number Formatting

- REQ-I18N-12: All displayed dates, times, and numbers MUST use locale-aware formatters — never hardcoded format strings
- REQ-I18N-13: 12-hour vs 24-hour clock MUST follow the user's locale preference (and respect device-level overrides where available)
- REQ-I18N-14: Calendar systems (Hijri for Arabic locales, Buddhist for Thai, etc.) SHOULD be supported alongside Gregorian where culturally expected
- REQ-I18N-15: All timestamps MUST be stored internally as UTC; locale conversion happens at display time only
- REQ-I18N-16: Relative time strings ("3 hours ago", "yesterday") MUST use locale-aware pluralization and phrasing

### 2.5 Pluralization & Grammar

- REQ-I18N-17: Every string containing a count MUST use ICU plural syntax supporting all 6 CLDR plural categories (zero, one, two, few, many, other) — simple string concatenation with numbers is prohibited
- REQ-I18N-18: Strings referencing gendered content types (movie vs series) MUST use ICU select syntax where target languages require grammatical gender agreement
- REQ-I18N-19: String interpolation MUST use named placeholders (not positional) to accommodate word-order differences across languages

### 2.6 Content Localization

- REQ-I18N-20: EPG data with multiple language variants (XMLTV `lang` attribute) MUST select the user's preferred language, falling back through a ranked language list
- REQ-I18N-21: VOD metadata MUST prefer the user's language, fall back to content original language, then to English
- REQ-I18N-22: Subtitle and audio track auto-selection MUST follow the user's language preferences (primary + fallback list)
- REQ-I18N-23: Search MUST work across languages — a user searching in Arabic MUST find content with English-only metadata via transliteration and diacritic-folded matching

### 2.7 Translation Workflow

- REQ-I18N-24: All user-facing strings MUST be externalized in translation files with no hardcoded text in component code
- REQ-I18N-25: Every translatable string MUST include context annotations: description, screen location, character length budget, placeholder documentation
- REQ-I18N-26: The app SHOULD support over-the-air translation updates without requiring a full app release
- REQ-I18N-27: A pseudo-localization build target SHOULD be maintained for QA — replacing characters with accented equivalents and padding strings by 40% to detect overflow

### 2.8 Locale-Specific Behavior

- REQ-I18N-28: Locale MUST be auto-detected from the platform on first launch, with user override available in settings
- REQ-I18N-29: Users MUST be able to set a ranked list of language preferences (primary UI language + content language fallback order)
- REQ-I18N-30: Content rating labels MUST display the correct regional rating system based on the user's locale (MPAA for US, BBFC for UK, FSK for Germany, etc.)
- REQ-I18N-31: Alphabetical sorting MUST use locale-aware collation (Arabic, CJK, and Latin sort orders differ fundamentally)

---

## 3. Analytics & Telemetry

### 3.1 Playback Quality Metrics

- REQ-ANALYTICS-01: The app MUST collect full-population (unsampled) quality-of-experience events: time-to-first-frame, rebuffer ratio, stall count, quality switches, playback failure rate, session duration, and completion rate
- REQ-ANALYTICS-02: Every playback event MUST be tagged with source type (IPTV, Plex, Emby, Jellyfin, DVR) for per-source health breakdowns
- REQ-ANALYTICS-03: No raw stream URLs, IP addresses, or profile names may appear in any analytics event payload — use hashed/pseudonymous identifiers only

### 3.2 Engagement & Content Metrics

- REQ-ANALYTICS-04: The app SHOULD track: sessions per user per day, channels watched, VOD items browsed, search queries (with zero-result flag), and feature usage
- REQ-ANALYTICS-05: Per-source health metrics MUST be tracked: sync success rate, average TTFF, failover frequency, EPG coverage percentage

### 3.3 Privacy-Respecting Collection

- REQ-ANALYTICS-06: Analytics consent MUST be collected at first launch, separate from account creation, with granular per-category toggles
- REQ-ANALYTICS-07: Profile identifiers in analytics MUST be pseudonymized (one-way hash with rotating salt)
- REQ-ANALYTICS-08: Kids profile analytics MUST stay on-device regardless of consent status (COPPA compliance) — no individual-level events sent to any server
- REQ-ANALYTICS-09: Data retention: raw events 30 days, aggregated metrics 24 months, crash reports 90 days, kids profile data 30 days maximum

### 3.4 Crash Reporting

- REQ-ANALYTICS-10: Crash reports MUST capture: exception type, symbolicated stack trace, app version, platform, OS version, device class, current screen, player state, and last 10 user actions (as anonymized event names, not payloads)
- REQ-ANALYTICS-11: Crash reports MUST NOT contain: stream URLs, profile names, IP addresses, or any user-entered text
- REQ-ANALYTICS-12: Debug symbols MUST be uploaded to the crash reporting service on every release build for proper symbolication

### 3.5 Feature Flags & A/B Testing

- REQ-ANALYTICS-13: A server-side feature flag system MUST be implemented for gradual rollout (1% → 5% → 20% → 50% → 100%) with automatic guardrail metric monitoring
- REQ-ANALYTICS-14: Any feature behind a flag MUST be disablable server-side without an app update (kill switch)
- REQ-ANALYTICS-15: Feature flags MUST be cached locally with a reasonable TTL; offline fallback MUST use last cached values or hardcoded safe defaults

### 3.6 Recommendation Signals

- REQ-ANALYTICS-16: Behavioral signals for recommendations MUST include: watch completion, watch duration, favorites, DVR scheduling, search-to-play conversion — each with time-decay weighting (recent signals dominate)
- REQ-ANALYTICS-17: For opted-out users, recommendations MUST use content-based filtering only (genre, language, year) with all computation on-device
- REQ-ANALYTICS-18: Cold-start protocol: onboarding genre picker (select from ~12 genre tiles, minimum 3) seeds initial recommendations; adapt aggressively after first 3-5 plays

---

## 4. Parental Controls (Deep Dive)

### 4.1 Content Rating System

- REQ-PARENT-01: The app MUST use a unified internal rating scale (7 tiers: Everyone, Parental Guidance, Kids+, Teen, Mature, Adult, Unrated) that maps to all regional systems (MPAA, BBFC, FSK, PEGI, ACB, CBFC, EIRIN)
- REQ-PARENT-02: The displayed rating label MUST use the user's regional system based on locale
- REQ-PARENT-03: Unrated content MUST default to blocked in kids profiles
- REQ-PARENT-04: Parents MUST be able to manually assign a rating to any channel or VOD item, overriding metadata

### 4.2 Content Blocking

- REQ-PARENT-05: Per-channel and per-title blocking MUST be available regardless of rating (block specific content even within allowed rating)
- REQ-PARENT-06: Category/genre blocking MUST allow parents to block entire genres (e.g., Horror, Crime, News)
- REQ-PARENT-07: Keyword-based blocking MUST scan EPG programme titles/descriptions and block matching programmes on a per-session basis
- REQ-PARENT-08: An allow-list (whitelist-only) mode MUST be available for the youngest age band — kids see only explicitly approved content
- REQ-PARENT-09: Blocked content MUST be completely hidden from kids profiles (not shown as "locked" — invisible in search, EPG, and browse)

### 4.3 Time-Based Restrictions

- REQ-PARENT-10: Daily viewing time limits MUST be configurable per kids profile with separate weekday/weekend values
- REQ-PARENT-11: Time-of-day restrictions (allowed viewing window) MUST be configurable with a "bedtime" countdown mode (warning → gentle stop → forced stop requiring parent PIN)
- REQ-PARENT-12: Remaining time MUST be displayed non-intrusively in the player for kids profiles
- REQ-PARENT-13: A "More Time" button (PIN-protected) MUST allow parents to grant extensions

### 4.4 Activity Monitoring

- REQ-PARENT-14: Parents MUST have access to per-kids-profile viewing history: what was watched, when (date only, not precise timestamp), and for how long
- REQ-PARENT-15: A weekly digest notification SHOULD be available (opt-in) summarizing each kids profile's viewing activity
- REQ-PARENT-16: Kids profile users MUST NOT be able to see or clear their own activity history
- REQ-PARENT-17: Activity data MUST be retained for 30-90 days and auto-deleted after

### 4.5 Profile Security

- REQ-PARENT-18: Profile creation MUST require the account password (prevents children from creating unrestricted profiles)
- REQ-PARENT-19: Exiting a kids profile MUST require PIN entry on all platforms
- REQ-PARENT-20: PIN recovery MUST be available via email verification only (no SMS — SIM swap risk)
- REQ-PARENT-21: After excessive failed PIN attempts, the profile MUST lock and require account-level re-authentication

### 4.6 Kids Profile UX

- REQ-PARENT-22: Kids profiles MUST have a visually distinct experience: simplified navigation (3 levels max), large interactive elements, no text-based search for youngest age band
- REQ-PARENT-23: No hover/auto-play previews in kids profiles — static thumbnails only
- REQ-PARENT-24: Auto-play next episode in kids profiles MUST have a longer countdown than adult profiles, giving a natural decision point
- REQ-PARENT-25: Kids profiles MUST NOT display: advertisements, in-app purchase prompts, subscription upsells, or cross-promotions for adult content
- REQ-PARENT-26: All administrative UI (source management, settings, DVR management) MUST be invisible in kids profiles

---

## 5. Backup, Restore & Migration

### 5.1 Backup Scope

**Included in backup:**
- Profiles (names, avatars, PIN hashes — never plaintext PINs)
- Source definitions (URLs, usernames; passwords encrypted separately)
- Channel order, groupings, hidden channels
- Favorites (per-profile)
- Watch history with resume positions
- DVR schedules and keyword rules
- Smart groups and EPG channel mappings
- Bookmarks, search history, saved layouts
- Playback and UI settings, parental control settings
- Notification preferences

**Excluded from backup:**
- Cached thumbnails, logos, EPG artwork
- Downloaded/recorded video files
- Temporary/buffer files, stream health metrics
- Session tokens (re-authenticate on restore)
- Any data derivable from source refresh (channel lists, EPG data, VOD catalogs)

### 5.2 Credential Handling in Backup

- REQ-BACKUP-01: Backup files MUST encrypt credentials separately using authenticated encryption (AES-256-GCM) with a user-supplied passphrase as the key source (via Argon2id KDF)
- REQ-BACKUP-02: The passphrase MUST NOT be stored anywhere by the app
- REQ-BACKUP-03: A "restore without credentials" fallback MUST import everything except secrets (user re-enters passwords manually)

### 5.3 Backup UX

- REQ-BACKUP-04: Manual backup MUST export to a single encrypted file that can be saved to local storage or cloud storage
- REQ-BACKUP-05: Automatic scheduled backup SHOULD run daily (non-blocking, background), retaining the last N backups (configurable, default 7)
- REQ-BACKUP-06: Backup destinations SHOULD include: local device storage, and major cloud storage providers appropriate for the platform

### 5.4 Restore Flow

- REQ-BACKUP-07: Selective restore MUST be available — a checklist of backup sections with item counts, allowing the user to choose which sections to import
- REQ-BACKUP-08: Three merge policies MUST be offered: Replace All (backup wins), Merge (backup wins on conflict), Merge (local wins on conflict)
- REQ-BACKUP-09: Restore MUST be cross-platform compatible — platform-specific settings silently ignored on unsupported platforms; credentials may require re-entry
- REQ-BACKUP-10: Restore progress MUST be shown with stage indicators; on mid-way failure, the system MUST roll back to pre-restore state
- REQ-BACKUP-11: A post-restore verification screen MUST show what was imported, what needs attention (sources requiring re-auth, unmatched DVR channels)

### 5.5 Device Migration

- REQ-BACKUP-12: A "Move to New Device" wizard SHOULD generate a QR code on the old device encoding a short-lived cloud download URL + decryption key; the new device scans to import
- REQ-BACKUP-13: Import from competitor apps (TiviMate, IPTV Smarters) SHOULD be supported by parsing their backup formats or extracting M3U/Xtream credentials
- REQ-BACKUP-14: Post-migration, a verification screen MUST highlight sources needing re-authentication and any imported items requiring attention

### 5.6 GDPR Data Export

- REQ-BACKUP-15: An in-app "Export my data" function MUST export all personal data in structured JSON within 30 days of request
- REQ-BACKUP-16: Export MUST include: profiles, watch history, favorites, settings, sources (minus passwords), bookmarks, search history
- REQ-BACKUP-17: Identity verification (re-authentication) MUST be required before export delivery

---

## 6. Deployment & Distribution

### 6.1 App Store Requirements

- REQ-DEPLOY-01: The app MUST meet platform-specific store requirements for TV apps (Android TV Leanback manifest declarations, tvOS SDK version requirements, Fire TV banner assets)
- REQ-DEPLOY-02: Required store assets MUST be maintained per platform: TV banner images, platform-specific screenshots, feature graphics

### 6.2 Update Mechanism

- REQ-DEPLOY-03: For store-distributed builds, platform-native auto-update MUST be the primary mechanism
- REQ-DEPLOY-04: For sideloaded/direct-download builds, a custom update checker MUST poll for new versions (throttled to once per 24 hours) and present a non-blocking update prompt with changelog
- REQ-DEPLOY-05: Forced update (minimum version gate) MUST be supported — when the current version is below the minimum, a blocking modal with only "Update Now" MUST appear
- REQ-DEPLOY-06: Update prompts MUST allow "Skip this version" for optional updates (suppressed until a newer version is available)

### 6.3 Beta Channel

- REQ-DEPLOY-07: Beta testing MUST use platform-native beta channels where available (Google Play closed testing, Apple TestFlight)
- REQ-DEPLOY-08: For platforms without native beta channels, direct download with a separate beta channel in the update checker MUST be provided
- REQ-DEPLOY-09: Beta builds MUST include enhanced crash reporting and an in-app feedback mechanism

### 6.4 Rollback & Kill Switch

- REQ-DEPLOY-10: Server-side feature flags MUST allow disabling any flagged feature instantly without an app update
- REQ-DEPLOY-11: Database schema migrations MUST be additive-only (new columns with defaults, new tables) — never remove columns in minor versions
- REQ-DEPLOY-12: Backup schema versioning MUST prevent restoring a newer-format backup into an older app version (clear error message)

---

## 7. Licensing & Legal

### 7.1 Open Source Attribution

- REQ-LEGAL-01: An open source attribution screen MUST be accessible from Settings → About → Licenses, listing all third-party dependencies with: library name, version, license type, copyright holder, and link to full license text
- REQ-LEGAL-02: Media player libraries using LGPL MUST be dynamically linked; the app MUST provide a link to the library source code and allow relinking
- REQ-LEGAL-03: A machine-readable Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) SHOULD be generated per release for compliance auditing

### 7.2 Terms of Service

- REQ-LEGAL-04: The Terms of Service MUST clearly state that the user is solely responsible for the legality of IPTV sources they configure — the app does not host, transmit, or verify content
- REQ-LEGAL-05: If any user-generated content features exist (shared playlists, community groups), a DMCA designated agent MUST be registered and a notice-and-takedown policy published
- REQ-LEGAL-06: The TOS MUST acknowledge geographic content licensing variation and disclaim responsibility for third-party source compliance

### 7.3 Privacy Policy

- REQ-LEGAL-07: The privacy policy MUST disclose: categories of data collected, purpose, legal basis, retention periods, third-party sharing, international transfer mechanisms, and user rights
- REQ-LEGAL-08: The privacy policy MUST be presented at first launch as a consent screen with plain-language summary and link to full text
- REQ-LEGAL-09: "Accept All" and "Decline Non-Essential" consent buttons MUST have equal visual weight — no dark patterns
- REQ-LEGAL-10: Persistent access to the full privacy policy, consent management, data export, and account deletion MUST be available in Settings → Privacy

---

## 8. Diagnostics & Observability

### 8.1 User-Facing Diagnostics

- REQ-DIAG-01: A diagnostics screen MUST be accessible from Settings (and from stream error states) showing:
  - **Per-stream**: current bitrate, buffer level, video/audio codec and resolution, dropped frames, connection latency, reconnection count
  - **Per-source**: last sync timestamp, sync error history, channel count, EPG coverage percentage, next scheduled sync
  - **System**: app version, platform, OS version, available storage, network type

### 8.2 EPG Health Monitoring

- REQ-DIAG-02: Stale EPG data MUST be detected (channel with no future programme data) and visually indicated in the EPG guide
- REQ-DIAG-03: Per-source EPG coverage metrics (% channels with data, % programme slots filled for next 24h/7d) SHOULD be displayed in source health settings

### 8.3 Source Health Dashboard

- REQ-DIAG-04: Each configured source MUST show a health summary: uptime (last 7 days), error rate, sync history (last 10 events with status)
- REQ-DIAG-05: Source health indicators MUST use a simple status system (healthy, degraded, offline) — visible in Settings → Sources, NOT on every content card

### 8.4 Diagnostic Log Export

- REQ-DIAG-06: An "Export Diagnostic Log" function MUST be available for support ticket creation
- REQ-DIAG-07: Exported logs MUST be automatically scrubbed of sensitive data (passwords replaced with [REDACTED], emails hashed)
- REQ-DIAG-08: Log export MUST include: last 24 hours of app events, errors, source sync history, and stream events
