# SRS Addendum 5 — Onboarding, Help & Discoverability, Web/PWA, Multi-Monitor

## CrispyTivi — Technology-Agnostic Requirements

**Supplements**: `.ai/SRS.md` and Addendums 1-4
**Date**: 2026-03-14

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Onboarding & First-Run Experience](#1-onboarding--first-run-experience)
2. [Help & Discoverability System](#2-help--discoverability-system)
3. [Web / PWA Platform Requirements](#3-web--pwa-platform-requirements)
4. [Multi-Monitor & External Display](#4-multi-monitor--external-display)

---

## 1. Onboarding & First-Run Experience

### 1.1 First-Launch Flow

- REQ-ONBOARD-01: First playback MUST be reachable in 3 steps or fewer from app launch (add source → validate → play)
- REQ-ONBOARD-02: The source setup wizard MUST validate URL/credentials inline before proceeding, with clear success/failure feedback (channel count on success, actionable error on failure)
- REQ-ONBOARD-03: The wizard MUST be re-enterable from Settings at any time without affecting existing data
- REQ-ONBOARD-04: On TV, every wizard step MUST be fully navigable with D-pad only
- REQ-ONBOARD-05: Every optional wizard step MUST have a visible, focusable "Skip" or "Do this later" affordance
- REQ-ONBOARD-06: Source format (M3U vs Xtream vs Stalker) SHOULD be auto-detected from the entered URL/credentials — the user should not need to know the protocol type
- REQ-ONBOARD-07: After first source sync, the app MUST land on a content screen (channel list or home) with content visible — never on a blank or settings screen
- REQ-ONBOARD-08: Everything beyond the first source (EPG, favorites, DVR, profiles, smart groups) MUST be deferred to post-first-play discovery

### 1.2 Empty States

Every screen MUST have a designed empty state that guides the user to the next action. No blank screens allowed.

| Screen | Empty State Behavior |
|---|---|
| Home (no sources) | Explain the app's purpose + prominent "Add Source" action |
| Channel List (no channels) | Explain that channels come from sources + link to source settings or refresh |
| Movies / Series (no VOD) | Explain that the source may not include VOD + option to add another source |
| EPG (no guide data) | Explain EPG requirement + link to add EPG URL in source settings |
| Favorites (none set) | Explain how to favorite (mention the shortcut key/button) + browse action |
| DVR Recordings (none) | Explain how to schedule + link to EPG guide |
| Search (no results) | Suggest different spelling or checking sources — never just "No results" |
| Continue Watching (no history) | Explain that history builds as you watch + browse action |

- REQ-ONBOARD-09: Every screen MUST have a designed empty state — no blank screens or unhandled null conditions
- REQ-ONBOARD-10: Empty states on TV MUST have a single clearly focused action button (maximum two options)
- REQ-ONBOARD-11: First-use empty states MUST visually hint at the feature's purpose (icon or illustration)
- REQ-ONBOARD-12: "No results" empty states MUST be visually distinct from "loading failed" states — different messaging and treatment
- REQ-ONBOARD-13: Empty state CTAs MUST link directly to the action that resolves the empty condition, not to a generic settings root

### 1.3 Getting Started Checklist

- REQ-ONBOARD-14: A "Getting Started" checklist card SHOULD appear on the Home screen when the user has not yet completed key setup steps
- REQ-ONBOARD-15: Checklist items: Add a source (auto-checked), Add EPG guide data, Create your first favorite, Set up DVR storage — each linking directly to the relevant action
- REQ-ONBOARD-16: Checklist state MUST be stored per-profile
- REQ-ONBOARD-17: The checklist MUST be manually dismissible at any time regardless of completion state
- REQ-ONBOARD-18: The checklist MUST auto-dismiss when all items are completed

### 1.4 Progressive Feature Discovery

Advanced features MUST NOT overwhelm first-time users. They are surfaced contextually as the user gains experience.

- REQ-ONBOARD-19: Advanced features (multiview, DVR keyword rules, smart groups, equalizer) MUST NOT be promoted to users who have not yet used the related basic features
- REQ-ONBOARD-20: Contextual "Did you know?" tips MUST appear at most once per session, triggered when a relevant context is first entered (e.g., first EPG visit → "Long-press to set a reminder")
- REQ-ONBOARD-21: Contextual tips MUST be short (maximum 2 lines), positioned to not cover focused content, and dismissible with a single keypress
- REQ-ONBOARD-22: Dismissed tips MUST never reappear — tracked per profile
- REQ-ONBOARD-23: Coach mark sequences (spotlight + explanation) MUST be limited to 4 steps maximum and always skippable

---

## 2. Help & Discoverability System

### 2.1 Shortcut Reference Panel

- REQ-HELP-01: A shortcut reference panel MUST be accessible via a dedicated key (? or Help) on desktop/web at any time
- REQ-HELP-02: The panel MUST be organized by feature area (Player, Navigation, DVR, Search), not alphabetically by key
- REQ-HELP-03: The panel MUST be searchable (filter field narrows the list by keyword)
- REQ-HELP-04: The panel MUST show platform-appropriate glyphs: keyboard key labels on desktop, gamepad button icons on gamepad, color button squares on TV remote
- REQ-HELP-05: The panel MUST be dismissible with Back/Escape and fully navigable by keyboard and D-pad

### 2.2 Player Contextual Hint Bar

- REQ-HELP-06: The player OSD MUST include a contextual hint bar showing active button/key mappings for the current state
- REQ-HELP-07: The hint bar MUST use platform-appropriate input device glyphs matching the currently active input method
- REQ-HELP-08: The hint bar MUST update instantly when screen, focused element, or player state changes
- REQ-HELP-09: On first encounter with a screen, the hint bar SHOULD be visible longer than on subsequent visits
- REQ-HELP-10: The hint bar MUST NOT be the sole way to discover actions — all actions MUST also be in context menus (per SRS-ADDENDUM-2 REQ-INPUT-18)

### 2.3 Interactive Guided Tour

- REQ-HELP-11: A guided tour MUST be available for first-time users, covering key features in an interactive walkthrough
- REQ-HELP-12: Tour steps MUST be fully navigable via D-pad, gamepad, keyboard, and touch
- REQ-HELP-13: Tour MUST be skippable at any step with the Back button
- REQ-HELP-14: Interactive "try it now" prompts SHOULD wait for actual user input before advancing (learn-by-doing pattern)
- REQ-HELP-15: Tour progress MUST be stored per-profile and resumable on next app launch if interrupted
- REQ-HELP-16: Tour MUST be re-accessible from a Help menu at any time
- REQ-HELP-17: Maximum 6 steps per tour sequence to prevent fatigue

### 2.4 Contextual Help & Tooltips

- REQ-HELP-18: Help MUST be accessible from every primary screen within 2 navigation moves on TV
- REQ-HELP-19: Settings screens MUST implement a focus-triggered description region that updates as focus moves between options (no hover-based tooltips on TV)
- REQ-HELP-20: Long-press on any focused settings element SHOULD show a brief tooltip explaining the option
- REQ-HELP-21: Every error message MUST include at least one actionable next step; error messages linking to help content MUST deep-link to the relevant section

### 2.5 First-Use Hint Cards

- REQ-HELP-22: When a user navigates to a major feature screen for the first time, a non-blocking hint card MUST explain what the feature does and what the primary action is
- REQ-HELP-23: Hint cards MUST NOT block navigation or playback — they overlay non-intrusively
- REQ-HELP-24: Hint cards MUST auto-dismiss after a period of inactivity
- REQ-HELP-25: If the user navigates away without explicitly dismissing, the hint is "snoozed" and reappears on the next visit (up to 3 times before permanent auto-dismissal)
- REQ-HELP-26: Hint card state (shown/dismissed/snoozed) MUST be stored per profile

---

## 3. Web / PWA Platform Requirements

### 3.1 Service Worker & Offline Capability

- REQ-WEB-01: The app shell (HTML, CSS, JS), static assets (icons, fonts), and user preferences MUST be precached for offline app launch
- REQ-WEB-02: Channel list and EPG data MUST use stale-while-revalidate caching (serve cached instantly, refresh in background)
- REQ-WEB-03: Thumbnail and channel logo images MUST be cached with time-based expiry
- REQ-WEB-04: Video streams MUST NOT be cached by the service worker (too large; DRM prevents it)
- REQ-WEB-05: The web app MUST be functional for browsing (channels, EPG, settings) with no network connection using cached data — streaming requires network

### 3.2 PWA Install Prompt

- REQ-WEB-06: The PWA install prompt MUST NOT appear on the first session or first page load
- REQ-WEB-07: The prompt SHOULD appear after the user has demonstrated engagement (played content, added a favorite, or returned for a second session)
- REQ-WEB-08: The prompt MUST be dismissible and MUST NOT re-appear for at least 7 days after dismissal
- REQ-WEB-09: A persistent "Add to Home Screen" entry SHOULD be available in the app's side menu for users who dismissed the prompt

### 3.3 Browser Compatibility & Feature Gaps

The web version MUST function across major browsers with graceful degradation for missing features:

| Feature | Full Support | Partial/No Support | Degradation Strategy |
|---|---|---|---|
| DRM (Widevine) | Chrome, Firefox, Edge | Safari (FairPlay only) | Route to FairPlay on Safari; show clear error if DRM unavailable |
| Picture-in-Picture | Chrome, Firefox, Edge | Safari mobile, iOS PWA | Disable PiP button; show explanation |
| Push Notifications | Chrome, Firefox, Edge | Safari (macOS 14+ only) | Use in-app notification center as primary; note push limitation |
| Equalizer (Web Audio) | Chrome, Edge | Firefox (partial), Safari (limited) | Gracefully degrade to simplified or disabled equalizer |
| File downloads | Chrome, Edge (File System Access) | Firefox, Safari | No offline download on web; explain and suggest native app |
| Window Management (multi-monitor) | Chrome 100+, Edge 100+ | Firefox, Safari | Single-window fallback; note limitation |

- REQ-WEB-10: When a feature is unavailable due to browser limitations, the UI MUST explain why and suggest an alternative (different browser or native app install)
- REQ-WEB-11: "Install the native app" suggestions MUST only appear contextually when the user encounters a browser limitation — never as a generic nag
- REQ-WEB-12: The web app MUST detect available DRM systems at startup and route streams to the appropriate system

### 3.4 Responsive Layout for Browser Windows

The web app MUST support fluid window resizing across 4 layout tiers:

| Tier | Width | Layout |
|---|---|---|
| Compact | < 600px | Single-column, no sidebar, bottom navigation |
| Medium | 600-1024px | Split view, collapsible sidebar |
| Expanded | 1024-1440px | Full desktop, persistent sidebar, multi-column grids |
| Wide | > 1440px | Extra-wide, dual-pane EPG, larger card grids |

- REQ-WEB-13: Layout MUST adapt fluidly to window resizing without content reflow artifacts or layout flash
- REQ-WEB-14: Components SHOULD use container-relative sizing so they adapt to their container width, not just the viewport

---

## 4. Multi-Monitor & External Display

### 4.1 Display Selection

- REQ-DISPLAY-01: On desktop platforms, the player settings MUST allow selection of which connected display receives fullscreen video output
- REQ-DISPLAY-02: The display list MUST refresh dynamically when external displays are connected or disconnected at runtime
- REQ-DISPLAY-03: On web (browsers supporting the Window Management API), the app SHOULD support projecting video to a secondary display via a dedicated fullscreen window

### 4.2 Detached Video Window

- REQ-DISPLAY-04: Desktop builds MUST support detaching the video into a separate, moveable, resizable window — allowing "controls on primary monitor, video on secondary"
- REQ-DISPLAY-05: When video is on a secondary display, the primary window MUST retain full playback controls (transport, EPG mini-guide, queue, volume)
- REQ-DISPLAY-06: Closing the detached video window MUST return video to the main app window (not stop playback)

### 4.3 DPI & Resolution Handling

- REQ-DISPLAY-07: The app MUST handle DPI changes when a window is dragged between displays with different pixel densities (e.g., HiDPI laptop → 1080p TV) without visual artifacts, scaling issues, or layout reflow
- REQ-DISPLAY-08: Video rendering MUST adapt to the target display's native resolution — not the primary display's resolution

### 4.4 Audio Routing

- REQ-DISPLAY-09: An audio output device selector MUST be available in Player Settings on desktop platforms (Windows, Linux) — allowing the user to choose between laptop speakers, HDMI audio, Bluetooth, USB audio, etc.
- REQ-DISPLAY-10: On platforms where audio routing is OS-controlled (macOS), the app MUST document this limitation and link to OS audio settings

### 4.5 Mobile External Display

- REQ-DISPLAY-11: On mobile platforms with desktop mode (Samsung DeX), the app MUST behave as a fully resizable window — no locked aspect ratios or forced fullscreen
- REQ-DISPLAY-12: On tablet platforms with windowing (iPad Stage Manager), the app MUST respect the OS-assigned window bounds
</file>

