## 3. Business Logic & Backend

> **Design Freedom**: The algorithms and processing strategies below define *what* must be computed and the expected behavior. Implementations may use any technology, architecture, or optimization strategy. The grouping of responsibilities (which service owns which algorithm) may be restructured.

### 3.1 Content Source Synchronization

The system synchronizes content from multiple provider types. Each sync operation downloads, parses, and persists content to the local database.

#### 3.1.1 M3U Playlist Sync

**Input**: HTTP URL pointing to `.m3u` or `.m3u8` file
**Process**:
1. Download playlist content via HTTP
2. Parse `#EXTM3U` header for EPG URL (`url-tvg` or `x-tvg-url` attribute)
3. For each `#EXTINF` directive, extract: `tvg-id`, `tvg-name`, `group-title`, `logo`, `catchup` metadata, `user-agent`
4. Next non-comment line after `#EXTINF` is the stream URL
5. Detect resolution from channel name or attributes (4K/UHD/2160P, FHD/1080P, HD/720P, SD/480P)
6. Generate stable channel ID: SHA-256 hash of stream URL (first 16 hex chars)
7. Extract VOD items if present (movie/series entries in playlist)
8. Batch upsert channels and VOD to database
9. Return sync report: channel count, groups discovered, VOD count, EPG URL

**Output**: `SyncReport { channels_count, channel_groups[], vod_count, vod_categories[], epg_url? }`
**Error Handling**: Log per-entry parse errors but continue; return valid items + error list

#### 3.1.2 Xtream Codes API Sync

**Input**: Base URL + username + password
**Process**:
1. Verify credentials via account info endpoint
2. Fetch live categories -> resolve IDs to names
3. Fetch live streams -> parse channels with category resolution
4. Fetch VOD categories -> resolve names
5. Fetch VOD streams -> parse movies
6. Fetch series -> parse series and episodes (with `series_id` parent links)
7. Batch upsert all content to database
8. Emit real-time progress events per phase (downloading/parsing/saving, 0.0-1.0)

**Stream URL Formats**:
- Live: `{base}/live/{user}/{pass}/{stream_id}.ts`
- VOD: `{base}/movie/{user}/{pass}/{stream_id}.{ext}`
- Series: `{base}/series/{user}/{pass}/{stream_id}.{ext}`
- Catchup: `{base}/timeshift/{user}/{pass}/{duration_min}/{start_utc}/{stream_id}.ts`

**Credential Handling**: Percent-encode username and password for URL safety

#### 3.1.3 Stalker Portal Sync

**Input**: Portal URL + MAC address + device ID
**Process**:
1. Discover portal path: try 4 known paths in order (`/stalker_portal/server/load.php`, `/portal.php`, `/server/load.php`, `/c/`)
2. Two-step authentication: handshake (get token) -> do_auth (authenticate with MAC + device ID)
3. Fetch genres (categories), paginated
4. Fetch live streams, paginated (100-page safety limit)
5. Fetch VOD items, paginated
6. Fetch series and episodes, paginated
7. Save all to database

**Session Management**: Token + MAC cookie per session; `User-Agent: MAG250/1.0 (CrispyTivi)`

#### 3.1.4 EPG Synchronization

**Input**: XMLTV URL (from source EPG URL or global EPG URL setting)
**Process**:
1. Check cooldown: 4-hour minimum between fetches per URL (bypass with force flag)
2. Download XML content
3. Parse `<channel>` blocks -> build channel display name map
4. Parse `<programme>` blocks -> extract title, start, stop, description, category, icon
5. Match EPG channels to local channels using 6-strategy matching (see 3.2.3)
6. Save entries with source priority: lower `sort_order` source wins for overlapping `(channel_id, start_time)` slots
7. Return count of inserted/replaced entries

**Timestamp Formats**: `YYYYMMDDHHMMSS +ZZZZ` (primary), RFC 3339 (fallback)

### 3.2 Algorithms

#### 3.2.1 Content Recommendation Engine

**Input**: VOD items, channels, watch history, favorite IDs, current timestamp
**Output**: Ordered list of recommendation sections, each containing ranked items with reason text

**Algorithm Sections** (7 types, selected based on history depth):

| Section | Trigger | Strategy |
|---|---|---|
| Cold Start | History < 5 items | New releases + top-rated items |
| Top Picks | Always | High-rated items matching user's genre preferences |
| Because You Watched | When specific titles have been watched | Related content from same series/genre as recently watched |
| Genre Affinity | When genre frequency map is computable | Build frequency map of watched genres; recommend high-scoring unwatched items |
| Popular in Genre | When a dominant genre exists | Top items in user's most-watched genre |
| New for You | When new content matching preferences exists | Recently added content matching preferred genres |
| Trending | Always | Most-watched items across all profiles recently |

**Watch Signal Scoring**:
- Items watched > 95% of duration = "finished" (strong signal)
- Items watched 1-95% = "interested" (moderate signal)
- Unwatched items = ignored

#### 3.2.2 Search

**Input**: Query string + filter options
**Filter Options**: content types (channels/movies/series/EPG), search in descriptions, category filter, year range
**Process**:
1. Lowercase and tokenize query
2. For each enabled content type, match against normalized name (always) + description (if enabled)
3. Substring matching on normalized names
4. Group results by content type

**Output**: `SearchResults { channels[], movies[], series[], epg_programs[] }`

#### 3.2.3 EPG Channel Matching

Six strategies applied in order of confidence:

| Priority | Strategy | Confidence |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Exact `tvg_id` match + normalized name match | 1.00 |
| 2 | `tvg_id` + normalized name both match | 0.95 |
| 3 | EPG channel display name fuzzy match | 0.90 |
| 4 | Exact `tvg_id` match only | 0.65 |
| 5 | Normalized name fuzzy match | 0.50 |
| 6 | Call sign extraction (e.g., "WABC" in parentheses) | 0.40 |

User-locked mappings are never overwritten.

#### 3.2.4 Stream Failover & Health Scoring

**Purpose**: When a stream fails, rank alternative streams for automatic failover.

**Alternative Confidence Tiers**:
- 1.0: Exact name match
- 0.95: Same `tvg_id`
- 0.90: EPG + name match
- 0.65: EPG match only
- 0.60: Call sign match
- 0.50: Normalized name match (after stripping quality/region tags)

**Health Score** (0.0-1.0, composite):
- Stall count (weight 50%): fewer stalls = higher score
- Average buffer duration (weight 30%): capped at 10s
- Time-to-first-frame (weight 20%): lower is better, capped at 10s
- Exponential decay: 7-day half-life (older data weights less)

**Final Ranking**: `confidence * 0.6 + health_score * 0.4`

**Filtering**: Exclude alternatives from same source (prefer source diversity)

#### 3.2.5 Channel Sorting & Filtering

**Sort Modes**:
- Default: by group, then channel number, then name
- Alphabetical: case-insensitive
- Recently watched: by last-watched timestamp descending
- Date added: by import timestamp descending
- Manual: user-defined sort index per channel

**Filtering**: Applies search query, hidden groups, hidden channel IDs, duplicate suppression, source filter

**Special Group**: Favorites group (starred channels) always available

#### 3.2.6 VOD Sorting & Categorization

**Sort Options**: recently added, name (A-Z/Z-A), year descending, rating descending
**Category Building**: Extract unique categories from items, group by content type (movie vs series)
**Series Progress**: Aggregate watched episodes per series, compute next unwatched episode

#### 3.2.7 Duplicate Detection

**Algorithm**: Normalize all stream URLs (lowercase, strip query params), group by normalized URL
**Output**: Groups of 2+ channels sharing same stream, with first-in-input-order marked as preferred

#### 3.2.8 Watch History & Continue Watching

**In-Progress Detection**: `position > 0 AND position < 95% of duration`
**Continue Watching**: Filter in-progress items, sort by `last_watched` descending, limit to 20
**Series Tracking**: Aggregate episodes by `series_id`, determine next unwatched episode
**History ID Generation**: SHA-256 hash of stream URL (first 8 bytes, hex-encoded) for stable dedup

#### 3.2.9 Catchup/Timeshift URL Building

**Xtream Format**: `{base}/timeshift/{user}/{pass}/{duration_min}/{start_utc}/{stream_id}.ts`
**Stalker Format**: Append `?utc={start}&lutc={end}` to stream URL
**Validation**: Entry must be in past and within channel's `catchup_days` window

#### 3.2.10 DVR Scheduling

**Recurring Expansion**: Take `recur_days` bitmask (Sun=1..Sat=64) and date range, expand to concrete instances
**Conflict Detection**: Two recordings overlap if time ranges intersect on same device
**Start Detection**: Find recordings whose start time is within margin (default 120s) of current time

#### 3.2.11 DVR Storage Management

**File Classification**: By extension (`.ts`/`.mp4` = Recording, `.vtt` = Subtitle, `.bif` = Thumbnail)
**Storage Breakdown**: Sum bytes per file type, calculate percentages
**Cleanup Ordering**: Sort by modified time descending (FIFO cleanup)

#### 3.2.12 Cloud Sync & Merge

**Direction Determination**: Compare `exported_at` timestamps to decide cloud-to-local vs local-to-cloud
**Merge Strategy**:
- Timestamped entries: newer wins
- Lists (favorites, orders): deduplicate by ID, union
- Profiles: merge by ID, newer fields win
- Settings: merge with change timestamps
- Watch history: merge by ID, pick newer position/timestamp

**Merged Entities**: Profiles, favorites (channel + VOD), channel orders, profile-source access, settings, watch history, recordings, storage backends

#### 3.2.13 Cryptographic Operations

- SHA-256 hashing for PIN storage and stream URL hashing
- HMAC-SHA256 for AWS Signature Version 4 (S3 storage backend)
- AWS SigV4 full request signing for S3-compatible storage

#### 3.2.14 PIN Security & Lockout

- PIN stored as SHA-256 hash
- Constant-time comparison for verification
- Lockout after N failed attempts (configurable)
- Lockout expiry tracking with remaining time calculation

#### 3.2.15 Permission & Access Control

**DVR Permissions by Role**:
- Admin: full access to all recordings
- Full DVR: view all, delete own only
- View Only: view own recordings only
- Restricted: no DVR access

**Source Filtering**: Content filtered by profile's source access grants; children only see approved sources

#### 3.2.16 Text & URL Normalization

- Name normalization: lowercase, strip non-alphanumeric (except spaces), collapse whitespace
- URL normalization: lowercase, strip query params and fragments
- API base URL canonicalization: extract scheme://host[:port], omit default ports
- MAC address validation: `XX:XX:XX:XX:XX:XX` pattern
- Base64 auto-decode: detect and decode if valid UTF-8

#### 3.2.17 Category Resolution

- Map numeric category IDs (from Xtream/Stalker APIs) to human-readable names
- Build category -> name lookup for channel group assignment

#### 3.2.18 Group Icon Assignment

- Map channel group names to semantic emoji/icons (e.g., "Sports" -> football icon, "News" -> newspaper icon)

#### 3.2.19 Timezone Handling

- EPG time formatting with arbitrary timezone offsets (including fractional, e.g., +5:30 for IST)
- Duration formatting: minutes -> "Xh Ym"
- DST-aware timezone offset calculation

### 3.3 Parsing Engines

| Parser | Input Format | Output |
|---|---|---|
| M3U | `#EXTM3U` + `#EXTINF` plaintext | Channels + EPG URL |
| EPG/XMLTV | XML with `<channel>` and `<programme>` elements | EPG entries mapped to channels |
| Xtream | JSON from Xtream Codes API | Channels, VOD, series, EPG |
| Stalker | JSON from Stalker Portal API | Channels, VOD, series |
| VOD | JSON/M3U with movie/series metadata | VOD items with hierarchy |
| VTT | WebVTT with sprite metadata headers | Thumbnail sprite sheets for seek preview |
| S3 | XML ListBucketResult | File listing with metadata |
| BIF | Binary BIF format (magic header + JPEG index) | Thumbnail index for seek preview |

### 3.4 HTTP Client & Resilience

**Two Client Profiles**:

| Profile | Connect Timeout | Total Timeout | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|
| Standard | 15s | 120s | Playlist/EPG/stream fetching |
| Fast | 5s | 10s | Credential verification, URL checks |

**Connection Pool**: 4 idle connections per host, 60s TCP keepalive
**Redirect Limits**: 5 (standard), 3 (fast)
**Compression**: Gzip auto-decompression
**TLS**: Per-source toggle for accepting self-signed certificates

**Resilience Layer**:
- Retry on transient failures
- UTF-8 decode with replacement characters
- Invalid JSON escape sequence fixing (`\0`, `\x`, `\a`, lone surrogates)
- Truncated JSON array recovery (find last `}`, close with `]`)
- Missing opening quote repair in JSON values

### 3.5 Logo Resolution

**Source**: GitHub tv-logos repository (CDN + API)
**Resolution Strategy** (4-tier cascade):
1. Exact normalized name match
2. Alias variants (strip prefixes/suffixes, add `-network`, `-channel`)
3. Prefix match (prefer `-logo` variants)
4. Contains match (prefer closest length)

**Caching**: 24-hour TTL on logo index

### 3.6 App Update Checking

**Source**: GitHub Releases API
**Process**: Fetch latest release tag -> semver comparison against current version -> platform-specific asset matching (`.apk`, `.msix`, `.exe`, `.deb`, `.dmg`, etc.)

### 3.7 State Management Rules

**Event-Driven Updates**: Every data mutation emits a typed event through an event bus:

| Event | Trigger |
|---|---|
| BulkDataRefresh | Full data reload needed |
| ChannelsUpdated | Channel list changed |
| VodUpdated | VOD list changed |
| ProfilesUpdated | Profile list changed |
| SettingsUpdated | Settings changed |
| WatchHistoryUpdated | Watch history entry changed |
| RecordingsUpdated | Recording list changed |
| SourcesUpdated | Source list changed |
| SyncStarted / SyncProgress / SyncCompleted | Source sync lifecycle |

**Provider Dependencies**: Settings notifier -> Cache service -> Backend. Backend change events trigger cascading UI rebuilds through the reactive state tree.

